  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 34.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And he did that which was right in the sight of the Lord: he did according to all that his father Uzziah had done.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The author of Chronicles says the same, but adds, very pertinently, \"Howbeit he entered not into the temple of the Lord\" - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " he did not repeat his father's act of impiety. Josephus is still warmer in his praises. \"This king,\" he says (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "l.s.c",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".), \"was deficient in no manner of virtue; but was at once pious in things pertaining to God, and just in those pertaining to men. He was careful and watchful over the city; whatever needed reparation or adornment, he labored to supply strenuously, as the porticoes in the temple and the gates thereof; and where any part of the wall had gone to ruin, he raised it up again, and built towers of vast size and difficult to capture. And in all other matters pertaining to the kingdom, where there had been neglect, he applied great care and attention.\" 2 Kings 15:34",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Reign of Jotham of Judah (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 27:1-9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 15:32",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". \"In the second year of Pekah Jotham began to reign.\" This agrees with the statement in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 15:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", that Pekah became king in the last year of Uzziah, supposing that it occurred at the commencement of the year. Jotham's sixteen years therefore came to a close in the seventeenth year of Pekah's reign (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 16:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). His reign was like that of his father Uzziah (compare ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 15:34",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 15:35",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 15:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 15:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), except, as is added in Chr. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 15:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", that he did not force himself into the temple of the Lord, as Uzziah had done (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 26:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). All that is mentioned of his enterprises in the account before us is that he built the upper gate of the house of Jehovah, that is to say, that he restored it, or perhaps added to its beauty. The upper gate, according to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 9:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " compared with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 8:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 8:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ",",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 8:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 8:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", is the gate at the north side of the inner or upper court, where all the sacrifices were slaughtered, according to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 40:38-43",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". We also find from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 27:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". that he built against the wall of Ophel, and several cities in the mountains of Judah, and castles and towers in the forests, and subdued the Ammonites, so that they paid him tribute for three years. Jotham carried on with great vigour, therefore, the work which his father had began, to increase the material prosperity of his subjects. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]